{{Infobox book | name = An Introduction to Zen Buddhism | translator = | image = Zen Buddhism (book).jpg | caption = Cover to 1991 [[Grove Press]] edition | author = [[D.T. Suzuki]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = Japan | language = | series = | subject = [[Zen Buddhism]] | published = 1934 (Eastern Buddhist Society) | media_type = Print | pages = 130 | isbn = 0-8021-3055-0 | isbn_note = (1991 edition) | dewey= 294.3/927 20 | congress= BQ9265.4 .S95 1991 | oclc= 23975828 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} {{ZenBuddhism}}
'''''An Introduction to Zen Buddhism''''' is a 1934 book about [[Zen Buddhism]] by [[D.T. Suzuki|Daisetz Teitaro Suzuki]]. First published in [[Kyoto]] by the [[Eastern Buddhist Society]], it was soon published in other nations and languages, with an added preface by [[Carl Jung]]. The book has come to be regarded as "one of the most influential books on Zen in the West".<ref>{{cite book | title = Complete Book of Zen | author = Wong Kiew Kit | publisher = Tuttle Publishing | year = 2002 | isbn = 0-8048-3441-5 | page = 240}}</ref>
==Overview== The book grew out of Suzuki's 1914 publications for the Japanese journal ''New East''. Although the editor, Robertson Scott, suggested that Suzuki publish them in book form, he did not decide to do so until after the 1927 publication of his book ''Zen Essays'', which he decided would be "too heavy" as an introduction to Zen for beginners.<ref name=Preface>{{cite book | last = Suzuki | first = Daisetz Teitaro | publisher = Grove Press | year = 1991 | edition = reissue |title=An Introduction to Zen Buddhism |isbn=0-8021-3055-0 | page = 7}}</ref> Suzuki intended the resultant volume, 1934's ''An Introduction to Zen Buddhism'', to be used as a companion with the contemporaneously published ''Manual of Zen Buddhism''.<ref name=Preface/>
==Synopsis== {{Empty section|date=December 2009}}
==Release details== ''An Introduction to Zen Buddhism'' was published in 1934 in Kyoto by the Eastern Buddhist Society.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Sakanishi |first=Shio |year=1937 |title=review |page=445 |jstor=594535 |journal=Journal of the American Oriental Society |volume=57 |issue=4 |publisher=American Oriental Society |doi=10.2307/594535}}</ref> The Marshall Jones Company of [[Boston]] oversaw first publication in the United States. The 1939 German language edition was published with a preface by [[Carl Jung]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.abc.net.au/rn/ark/stories/2007/2004726.htm | title = D.T.Suzuki: Zen Pilgrim to the West | publisher = [[ABC Online]] | date = 19 August 2007 | accessdate = 2009-08-08}}</ref> In 1949, the book was reprinted in London and New York with Jung's preface, translated by Constance Rolfe, included.<ref>{{cite book | title = Writings through John Cage's music, poetry, and art| last = Bernstein | first = David W. | author2= Christopher Hatch | publisher = University of Chicago Press | year = 2001 | isbn = 0-226-04408-4 }}</ref>
